Indian Food Cookbook

Emily, Ellyn, Rachel, Gabe

2/17/2022

#Background of Project

Welcome to the Exploring India Cookbook, this an e-cook book that will allow you to select different dishes you would like to make depending on your diet, amount of time you have, the course you would like to make, or based on the region.

This project is separated into three parts: Section 1: Loading and Cleaning the Data Section 2: Questions about the data Section 3: Exploring India Cookbook App

##Section 1:

This section illustrates how we loaded the data, assessed the data structure, and cleaned the data. Load Library

library(tidyverse)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(paletteer)
library(janitor)
library(here)
library(naniar)
library(gapminder)
getwd()
  1. Load the data.
indian_food<- read_csv(here("indian_food_data.csv"))%>% clean_names()
  1. Structure of the data.
glimpse(indian_food)
summary(indian_food)

What are the variables?

names(indian_food)

Dealing with NAs

NAs in data is symbolized by a -1

indian_food<-indian_food%>%
  na_if("-1")

Counting Number of NAs

naniar::miss_var_summary(indian_food)

Split Ingredients Into Their Own Row

We noticed that the ingredients were listed in one row, so we separated them into their own rows.

indian_food<-indian_food%>%
  mutate_all(tolower)%>%
  transform(ingredients=str_split(ingredients,","))%>%
  unnest(ingredients)
indian_food

Adding Total Cook Time column which combines cook time and prep time.

indian_food<-indian_food%>%
  mutate(total_cook_time=as.numeric(cook_time)+as.numeric(prep_time))
indian_food

##Section Two: Questions about the data. 1. Does it take more or less time to cook vegetarian versus non-vegetarian dishes? For each diet, vegetarian and non-vegetarian, identify which dish takes the most and least amount of total cook time, prep time, and cook time.

  1. What course takes takes the longest time to make? What course takes the least amount of time to make?
  1. What is the relationship between flavor and diet (i.e.is there more spicy dishes in non-vegetarian compared to vegetarian?)
flavor_diet <- indian_food %>% 
  filter(!is.na(flavor_profile)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=diet, fill=flavor_profile))+
  geom_bar(na.rm=T, position="dodge",alpha=0.75, color="black") +
  labs(title = "Flavor in Relationship to Diet",
       x = "Diet",
       y = "Count") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))
flavor_diet

  1. Which ingredient is used the most for each region/state?
  1. What ingredient is used the most out of all the courses? What is the % of ingredient in all recipes.
  1. What diet is more associated with which region/state?
  1. What flavor profile is more associated with which region/state?
flavor_state <- indian_food %>% 
  filter(!is.na(flavor_profile)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(state)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=state, fill=flavor_profile))+
  geom_bar(na.rm=T, position="dodge",alpha=0.75, color="black") +
  labs(title = "Flavor in Relationship to State",
       x = "State",
       y = "Count") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.0), hjust = 0.5))+
   theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1)) 
flavor_state

flavor_region <- indian_food %>% 
  filter(!is.na(flavor_profile)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(region)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=region, fill=flavor_profile))+
  geom_bar(na.rm=T, position="dodge",alpha=0.75, color="black") +
  labs(title = "Flavor in Relationship to Region",
       x = "Region",
       y = "Count") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.0), hjust = 0.5))
flavor_region
